               <head>Taj Mahal, history and details, 2 items (a-b)</head>
               <msContents class="https://lccn.loc.gov/sh85132019 https://lccn.loc.gov/sh2008030123 https://lccn.loc.gov/n89199055">
                  <summary>Collection of two works describing the historical background and physical details of Agra’s monuments, with special reference to the Taj Mahal mausoleum, written as a guide for touring English officers. 
Volume not dated; datable to the early nineteenth century, probably written in Agra. 
Scribal nastaʿlīq and naskh; interlinear raqm annotations. 
Intermittent foliation in pencil. 
Lacking original binding. 
Folios bound; stains and wormholes. 
Seal erased at beginning. 
</summary>
                  <textLang mainLang="fa" otherLangs="ar">Persian and Arabic</textLang>
                  <msItem n="1" xml:id="Uk_Delhi_Persian_613-item1">
                     <locus from="1v" to="47r">ff. 1v-47r  </locus>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa" otherLangs="ar">Persian and Arabic </textLang>
                     <note>
                        <p>Untitled pseudo-historical biographical account by an unnamed author on the subject of <persName key="ark:/81055/vdc_100164657501.0x000001 viaf_42682528" role="subject">Mumtāz al-Zamānī Arjmand Bānū Baygum Mumtāz Maḥall</persName>, principal wife and empress-consort of the Timurid (Mughal) Emperor <persName key="ark:/81055/vdc_100164656355.0x000001 viaf_13108102" role="subject">Shāh Jahān I</persName>, augmented with further descriptions of their offspring; verses in praise of Mumtāz Maḥall attributed to Emperor Shāh Jahān I; inscriptions on the gates of the Sikandarah complex, including the tomb of Emperor Akbar I; inscribed cannons of Agra Fort; inscription on Prince Salīm’s black marble (sang-i Mūsá) throne in Agra Fort; inscriptions on the cenotaphs of Mumtāz Maḥall and Emperor Shāh Jahān I; inscriptions on the Motī Masjid of Agra Fort; lists of precious stones used in the <placeName>Rawz̤ah-'i munavvarah</placeName> or <placeName>Tāj Maḥall;</placeName> the names of various artisans; the total weight of precious stones; the total weight of wood; inscribed gates with lists of sūrahs of the <title key="work_22212">Qurʾān</title>; Agra’s climate and location; history of Agra; Emperor Akbar I’s Chishtī associations; birth of Prince Salīm (Emperor Jahāngīr); selections of poems by Princess <persName key="viaf_31132651" role="ctb">Zīb al-Nisāʾ bint ʿĀlamgīr I</persName>; genealogies of ‘Mughaliyah’ kings with coin legends, especially sajʿ verses, mentioning at end <persName key="viaf_2049153653237255900003" role="oth">Navvāb Ghāzī al-Dīn Ḥaydar of Avadh</persName> (d. 1242/1827). 
                        </p>
                        <p>Not dated at end. 
</p>
                        <p>Nastaʿlīq, with some Arabic quotations in naskh; interlinear raqm annotations. 
</p>
                     </note>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="2" xml:id="Uk_Delhi_Persian_613-item2">
                     <locus from="47v" to="114r">ff. 47v-114r </locus>
                     <author/>
                     <note>
                        <p>Untitled treatise assembling measurements and statistical details of the <placeName>Rawz̤ah-'i munavvarah</placeName> or Tāj Maḥall, written at the request of the <q>ṣāḥibān-i Angrīz</q> (English officers), by an unnamed author. 
                        </p>
                        <p>Not dated at end. 
</p>
                        <p>astaʿlīq, with some Arabic quotations in naskh; interlinear raqm annotations. 
</p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa" otherLangs="ar">Persian and Arabic</textLang>
                     <note/>
                  </msItem>
